Reverend '''William Douglass''' (1804{{ndash}}1862) was an abolitionist and church community leader. He preached for peace, racial equality, and education in the religious community.

==Early life==

Douglass was born in Baltimore, Maryland to African American parents who were not enslaved, although such was legal in Maryland at the time. He received his education from Rev. [[William Levington]], who founded the [[St. James Episcopal Church (Baltimore, Maryland)|St. James Church]] and School for African Americans in [[Baltimore, Maryland]] in 1824. While attending the St. James Church School, Douglass learned [[Hebrew (language)|Hebrew]], [[Greek (language)|Greek]], and [[Latin]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Bragg|first=George Freeman|title=History of the Afro-American Group of the Episcopal Church|year=1922|publisher=Church Advocate Press|location=Baltimore|page=95|url=https://play.google.com/store/books/details?id=j5zVAAAAMAAJ&rdid=book-j5zVAAAAMAAJ&rdot=1}}</ref>

==Career==
Douglass became a [[Methodist church|Methodist]] preacher on Maryland's Eastern shore. On June 22, 1834, [[Episcopal Diocese of Maryland|Maryland's]] bishop Stone ordained him an Episcopal deacon at [[St. Stephen's Episcopal Church (Earleville, Maryland)|St. Stephen's Church]] in [[Cecil County, Maryland|Cecil County]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Bragg|first=George Freeman|title=First Negro Priest on Southern Soil|year=1909|publisher=Church Advocate Press|location=Baltimore|pages=15–17}}</ref> Douglass then moved to [[Philadelphia]] to serve at the [[African Episcopal Church of St. Thomas]] where [[Episcopal Diocese of Pennsylvania|Pennsylvania]] Bishop [[Henry Onderdonk]] ordained him as a priest in 1836.<ref>{{cite book|last=Bragg|first=George Freeman|title=History of the Afro-American Group of the Episcopal Church|year=1922|publisher=Church Advocate Press|location=Baltimore|page= 78,187}}</ref> Douglass published his first book, a history of his church called, ''The Annals of the First African Church in the United States of America''.<ref>{{cite book|last=Douglass|first=William|title=The Annals of the First African Church in the United States of America|year=1862|publisher=King & Baird, printers|location=Philadelphia|url=https://play.google.com/store/books/details?id=BpUF9KVEGyQC}}</ref>

==Activism==

Rev. Douglass advocated education in trades and academia. He also believed deeply in the spread of peace above all else, despite the religious and racial unrest which beset Philadelphia in the 1830s and continued with the [[Know Nothing Movement]] in the 1840s and 1850s. He was active in the [[Anti-Slavery Society]].<ref>{{cite news|last=McCrummell|first=James|title=For Fedrick Douglass Paper Anti-Colonization and Anti Nebraska Meeting|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:EANX&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=12C59ADF3647A140&svc_dat=HistArchive:ahnpdoc&req_dat=0D3A241258B62B2A.|accessdate=March 23, 2013|newspaper=Fedrick Douglass' Paper|date=April 7, 1854}}</ref> He also advocated equal representation in the Episcopalian church, as in a pamphlet published in the year he died.<ref>{{cite book|last=Douglass|first=William|title=The Annals of the First African Church in the United States of America|year=1862|publisher=King & Baird, printers|location=Philadelphia|pages=160–169|url=https://play.google.com/store/books/details?id=BpUF9KVEGyQC.}}</ref>

==Family life==

Douglass married twice. His first wife was named Elizabeth.<ref>{{cite web|title=1850 United States Federal Census Record|url=http://www.Ancestry.com}}</ref> His second wife was Sarah Mapps Douglass, who survived him by two decades.<ref>https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/64604299</ref> Between his two marriages, Douglass produced nine children.<ref>{{cite web|title=1860 United States Federal Census Record|url=http://www.Ancestry.com}}</ref> His passion for education influenced his eldest daughters Sarah, Elizabeth, Mary, Caroline to acquire trades.<ref>{{cite web|title=1860 United States Federal Census Record|url=http://www.Ancestry.com}}</ref>

==Death==

Douglass died in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania in 1862. Records on Douglass were silenced{{clarify|date=April 2014}} after his death mainly due to the fact he was unsuccessful in gaining equal representation in the Episcopal diocese.{{citation needed|date=April 2014}}

